Bori Wildlife Sanctuary is a part of Pachmadhi biosphere reserve located in Central India. What's sets it apart from the famed Madhai sanctuary is the entry point. You have to enter from Bhaura on Itarsi - Betul highway. The entry gate is at Dhapada village . Some 10kms from Bhaura. Some good luxury resorts  have come up near gate . Entry is allowed from morning to 4 PM. Post that it's not allowed. Forest department charges Rs 3000 per vehicles for entry.
The best part is that you have to drive full 32 Kms in forest to reach camp site at core forest entry. This 32 Kms drive puts up surprises of wildlife. High ground Clearance vehicles are recommended though. But skillful hands can do with ordinary hatchbacks too.
Once at churna camp you can find rooms and facilities like a basic forest department rest house. It does the job efficiently. Just don't expect anything more. Even chilled water is not available. Electricity is there but limited upto lighting purposes. Mobile signals,No. A Typical point at the churna forest camp has some signals if you are lucky to find it.
Gypsy forest Safari e is available from churna base camp to core forest area for rupees 1700. But you have to do it on the very same day you have entered and reached the base if you stay and do the Gypsy Safari the next day you have to pay additional 1500.This part of pachmarhi biosphere has the highest possibility of spotting big cat family.  Spotting bison , blackbuck, spotted deer, wild boar, giant vultures is very easy .

Update- Now you have to take the gypsy compulsorily to Churna site at 32 kms. Your vehicle is not allowed and you have to leave your car at Gate. If you are staying at Churna camp , you can take your car. Even then you have to pay the gypsy charges of Rs 6600.

Still this is probably the only tiger sanctuary which allows to drive your vehicle inside which is a damn satisfying factor as per me.

Wildlife again is abundant and spotting tiger is rather easy due to small area and High concentration of big cat population.
Satish

Omkareshwar Jyotirling is the 4th of the 12 Jyotirlings in India. It's a giant temple of Lord Shiv in Ling-form, visited by thousands of devotees daily, situated on the banks of Narmada River.

From the pictures, it might have a strong resemblance to Rishikesh.

The temple is multi-storeyed, so for elderly people it might be tricky to climb all the stairs.

There is a small parking space, and you will find autorickshaws and totos (e-rickshaws) constantly going to and from the omkareshward Jyotirling. It's hardly 5 min from the Omkareshwar bus stand and there are buses from Indore (2-2.5 hours) /Ujjain (3.5-4 hours) going daily (check out online and prefer online booking else you might have to wait till the next bus arrives)

There is no entrance fees but if you wish not to stand in queue for 3-4 hours, I would recommend if possible get a VVIP ticket (costs 1100 for 2) or at least VIP ticket - there are no counters but you might come across multiple pundits at the entrance of the bridge that takes you to the temple. Do check on the Arti timings, as during then devotees aren't allowed to go inside the premises.

Also there is a small market, which has options for decent food, and some clothes-jewellery-souveniers if you want to purchase.

updatesFromCustomers.text:
Kandariya Mahadev Temple, Khajuraho, Madhya Pradesh, India

The Kandariya Mahadeva temple was built during the reign of Vidyadhara (r. c. 1003-1035 CE). At various periods of the reign of this dynasty many famous temples dedicated to Vishnu, Shiva, Surya, Shakti of the Hindu religion and also for the Thirthankaras of Jain religion were built. This is without any doubt the largest and most magnificent temple in Khajuraho. The elegant proportions of this building and its sculptural detailing are the most refined examples of this artistic heritage of central India.

Kandariya Mahadev shares its high platform with the small Mahadev shrine and the medium - sized Devi The Kandariya Mahadeva Temple, 31 metres (102 ft) in height, is in the western complex, which is the largest among the three groups of the Khajuraho complex of temples. This western group of temples, consisting of the Kandariya, Matangeshwara and Vishvanatha temples, is compared to a "cosmic design of a hexagon (a yantra or Cosmo gram)" representing the three forms of Shiva. The temple architecture is an assemblage of porches and towers which terminates in a shikhara or spire, a feature which was common from the 10th century onwards in the temples of Central India.

The temple is founded on a massive plinth of 4 meters (13 ft) height. The temple structure above the plinth is dexterously planned and pleasingly detailed. The superstructure is built in a steep mountain shape or form, symbolic of Mount Meru which is said to be the mythical source of creation of the world. The superstructure has richly decorated roofs which rise in a grand form terminating in the shikara, which has 84 miniature spires. The temple is in layout of 6 square kilometers (2.3 sq. mi), of which 22 are extant including the Ka·πá·∏çƒÅriyƒÅ MahƒÅdeva Temple. This temple is characteristically built over a plan of 31 meters (102 ft) in length and 20 metres (66 ft) in width with the main tower soaring to a height of 31 meters (102 ft), and is called the "largest and grandest temple of Khajuraho". A series of steep steps with high rise lead from the ground level to the entrance to the temple. The layout of the temple is a five-part design, a commonality with the Lakshmana and Vishvanatha temples in the Khajuraho complex. Right at the entrance there is torana, a very intricately carved garland which is sculpted from a single stone; such entrances are part of a Hindu wedding procession. The carvings on the entrance gate shows the "tactile quality of the stone and also the character of the symmetrical design" that is on view in the entire temple which has high relief carvings of the figurines. Finely chiseled, the decorative quality of the ornamentation with the sharp inscribed lines has "strong angular forms and brilliant dark-light patterns". The carvings are of circles, undulations giving off spirals or sprays, geometric patterns, masks of lions and other uniform designs which has created a pleasant picture that is unique to this temple, among all others in the complex.

Some background info on Pandav caves.
Capt. James Forsyth discovered Pachmarhi in 1857. That was also the time when he located five caves on a hill. In the local language, five means ‚ÄòPach; and a cave means ‚ÄòMarhi‚Äô. So the town came to be known as Pachmarhi. Later Britishers developed the town as the only hill station in central India, for their stay during hot Indian summers.
Pandav Caves is a very popular tourist attraction in Pachmarhi. It is a hill feature about 150 to 200 feet high, where around six room-shaped caves have been carved out of solid rock. As per the local folklore/legends, these caves are the ones where the Pandavas had spent time during their exile Five caves were for five brothers and the sixth cave was for Draupadi. Wife of Pandavas. A comparatively bigger and best-ventilated cave which also has beautiful carvings on the wall was occupied by Draupadi. The darkest cave was occupied by Bhima the toughest of them all.
As per another and more credible version, these caves were carved out of solid rock by Buddhist monks around the 10th ‚Äì 11th century for their stay and meditation. This version acquires more credibility as a remain of a brick-made stupa on top of the hill can still be seen.
Parking is not too far from the Pandav caves. The road from the parking to the garden at the base of the hill is lined on both sides by the usual street food, soft drink, tea coffee vendors and shops selling toys for kids and other small knickknacks.
At the end of the street, we entered a beautifully laid-out and maintained garden. The full beauty can really be seen and appreciated only when viewed from the top of the hill.
The path from the garden exits in an open space from where steps with safety railings have been made to facilitate climbing the hill which lead to Pandav Caves. One can make out that originally the steps were carved out from solid rock. Administration replaces all the damaged/worn out and unsafe steps with proper concrete steps. Steps and the railing make the climb quite comfortable and tourist-friendly.

Decent place to start with on pachmarhi trip but to be honest its just average. The place has a garden and caves where pandav used to stay. There was no proper story mentioned anywhere in the place. Also its not maintained properly, probably the only okayish point while traveling to pachmarhi. Do not spend more than 15 min here

Gauhar Mahal is a very beautiful and historical place in Bhopal. It is one of the beautiful heritage structures in Bhopal.
Gohar Mahal was constructed in the year 1820 by the first female ruler of Bhopal, Qudsia Begum who is popularly known as Gohar Begum. This three-storied palace was the residential as well as a working place for the Begum. Maintained by Madhya Pradesh Tourism, it is one of the finest specimens of architecture and craftsmanship of the Nawabi era. Built with a perfect blend of Hindu and Mughal styles of architecture, the palace is ornamented with intricate interior carvings and beautiful decorations on the exterior.
